2","1200":"1200","1199":"1199","1155":"1155","before April 1239":"vóór april 1239","Abt 1180":"circa 1180","Lèves, Chartres, Eure-et-Loir, Centre-Val de Loire, France":"Lèves, Eure-et-Loir, Frankrijk","Bruyères-le-Châtel, Palaiseau, Essonne, Île-de-France, France":"Bruyères-le-Châtel, Essonne, Île-de-France, Frankrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1180–before April 1239":"about 1180–before April 1239","1180–1239":"1180–1239","1185–1216":"1185–1216","1190–1240":"1190–1240","1200–1251":"1200–1251","1155–1215":"1155–1215","1155–1212":"1155–1212","1190":"1190","1251":"1251","1240":"1240","1185":"1185","1180":"1180","1239":"1239","1216":"1216","1215":"1215","1212":"1212","1200":"1200","1199":"1199","1155":"1155","before April 1239":"before April 1239","Abt 1180":"about 1180","Lèves, Chartres, Eure-et-Loir, Centre-Val de Loire, France":"Lèves, Eure-et-Loir, France","Bruyères-le-Châtel, Palaiseau, Essonne, Île-de-France, France":"Bruyères-le-Châtel, Essonne, Île-de-France, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lèves,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Lever   1 and 2, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","North German: patronymic from   Lever   3."],"variants":[{"name":"Lever","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): nickname for a fleet-footed or timid person, from Old French <i>levre</i> ‘hare’ (from Latin <i>lepus</i>, genitive <i>leporis</i>). It may also have been a metonymic occupational name for a hunter of hares.","English: topographic name for someone who lived in a place thickly grown with rushes, from Old English <i>lǣfer</i> ‘rush, reed, iris’. Compare   Laver  . Great and Little Lever in Greater Manchester are named with this word (in a collective sense), so the surname may also be a habitational name from these places.","Dutch and North German: from the medieval personal names <i>Lever</i>, a variant of <i>Liever</i> (see   Lieber  ), and <i>Levert</i>, a variant of <i>Lievert</i> (see   Liebhart  ). This surname is very rare in Germany."]},{"name":"Levis","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Levis</i> (Old English <i>Lēofhyse</i>, from <i>lēof</i> ‘dear, beloved’ + <i>hyse</i> ‘youth, warrior’).","English: occasionally perhaps from the Middle English personal name <i>Leve</i>, Old English <i>Lēofa</i> (male) or <i>Lēofe</i> (female), which derive from <i>lēof</i> ‘dear, beloved’, with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, since <i>Leve</i> is attested as a medieval surname.","English: perhaps also from Middle English <i>lef</i>, <i>leve</i>, plural <i>leves</i>, possibly representing Old English <i>lēaf</i> ‘leaf, foliage’ in some topographic sense, or Old English <i>hlīf</i> ‘shelter’."]}]},{"name":"VII","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Vivian   and   Vivien ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gaucelin VII de  Lèves, Seigneur de Lèves was born about 1180, in Lèves, Eure-et-Loir, France, his father, Geoffroi II de Lèves, was 26 and his mother, Marguerite de la Chapelle la Reine, was 26. He married Marguerite de Bruyères-le-Châtel in 1199. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died before April 1239, in Bruyères-le-Châtel, Essonne, Île-de-France, France."},"et":{"Abt 1180–before April 1239":"umbes 1180–enne aprilli 1239","1180–1239":"1180–1239","1185–1216":"1185–1216","1190–1240":"1190–1240","1200–1251":"1200–1251","1155–1215":"1155–1215","1155–1212":"1155–1212","1190":"1190","1251":"1251","1240":"1240","1185":"1185","1180":"1180","1239":"1239","1216":"1216","1215":"1215","1212":"1212","1200":"1200","1199":"1199","1155":"1155","before April 1239":"enne aprilli 1239","Abt 1180":"umbes 1180","Lèves, Chartres, Eure-et-Loir, Centre-Val de Loire, France":"Lèves, Eure-et-Loir, Prantsusmaa","Bruyères-le-Châtel, Palaiseau, Essonne, Île-de-France, France":"Bruyères-le-Châtel, Essonne, Île-de-France, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1180–before April 1239":"noin 1180–ennen vuotta huhtikuu 1239","1180–1239":"1180–1239","1185–1216":"1185–1216","1190–1240":"1190–1240","1200–1251":"1200–1251","1155–1215":"1155–1215","1155–1212":"1155–1212","1190":"1190","1251":"1251","1240":"1240","1185":"1185","1180":"1180","1239":"1239","1216":"1216","1215":"1215","1212":"1212","1200":"1200","1199":"1199","1155":"1155","before Apr